column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 ON AUGUST 3, 1994, A RELEASE FROM A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED BY CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PRODUCTION PERSONNEL. THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED ON THE TRANSPORTATION VEHICLE WHICH HAD TRANSPORTED THE WASTE FROM THE GENERATOR'S SITE. ALLIED SIGNAL, 11100 NORTH ORACLE ROAD, TUCSON, ARIZONA (AZD981421449) WAS THE GENERATOR. THE WASTE WAS BEING TRANSPORTED BY CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT (ILD099202681) TO CHEMICAL WAS MANAGEMENT'S HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE FACILITY (AZT050010180). THE WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED USING A UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANINFEST, MANIFEST DOCUMENT NUMBER 10247. THE WASTE SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY ON AUGUST 2, 1994 AFTER NORMAL BUSINESS HOURS. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE FACILITY'S ARIZONA HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT ACT PERMIT, ATTACHMENT C, SECTION 7.2, THE VEHICLE WAS ALLOWED TO ENTER THE FACILITY AND WAS SECURED WITHIN THE PERIMETER FENCING. THE FOLLOWING MORNING PRODUCTION PERSONNEL, IN PREPARATION FOR PROCESSING OF THE WASTE INTO STORAGE, NOTICED A RELEASE OF MATERIAL FROM THE RING TOP OF AN OPEN HEAD STEEL 55-GALLON DRUM. APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) POUNDS OF A HAZARDOUS WASTE, U.S. DOT DESCRIPTION, RQ, WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIALS, 3, UN1263, II, (ALCOHOL, METHYL ETHYL KETONE) HAD SEEPED FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM ONTO THE BED OF THE FLAT-BED TRAILER ON WHICH IT WAS STORED AND ONTO THE GROUND. THE RELEASE DID NOT CONSTITUTE A "REPORTABLE QUANTITY". THE APPARENT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS THE EXPANSION OF THE LIQUID DUE TO HEAT. THE BED AND SIDEBOARD OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WERE DECONTAMINATED WITH A DETERGENT SOLUTION. THE SOLUTION WAS ABSORBED USING TOWELING. ALL GRAVEL WHICH EXHIBITED VISIBLE STAINING WAS REMOVED. IN ADDITION, THE UNDERLYING SOILS, TO AN APPROXIMATE DEPTH OF THREE (3) INCHES, WERE REMOVED. ALL DECONTAMINATION MATERIALS, SOIL AND GRAVEL WERE MANAGED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE (F003, F005). FACILITY PERSONNEL DONNED STEEL-TOED BOOTS, TYVEK OUTER COVERING, LATEX INNER GLOVES WITH NITRILE OUTER GLOVES, FULL-FACE RESPIRATORS WITH ORGANIC VAPOR/HEPA CARTRIDGES FOR ALL OF THE ABOVE REFERENCED TASKS. CONTAMINATED PPE WAS ALSO MANAGED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE FACILITY PERMIT, ATTACHMENT G, SECTION 7.2, A SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED FROM THE SPILL AREA AND FOUR (4) BACKGROUND SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED FROM THE AGRICULTURAL FIELD ADJACENT TO THE FACILITY. THE SPILL AREA MEASURED APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN (15) INCHES EAST TO WEST AND THIRTEEN (13) INCHES NORTH TO SOUTH. THE ATTACHED SITE MAP INDICATES THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL. SUBSEQUENT TO REMEDIATION, THE RESULTANT EXCAVATION WAS SECURED WITH A CONTAINER AND WARNING TAPE.

DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON ROUTE 22 WHEN HE HAD TO MAKE A PANIC STOP. THE DRIVER SAID HE COULD FEEL SOMETHING MOVE IN THE TRAILER SO HE PULLED OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO CHECK IT. THE DRUM THAT WAS DAMAGED APPARENTLY SLID AGAINST A TOTE TANK CAUSING THE DRUM TO RUPTURE. THE PRODUC WAS CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND WITHIN A MATTER OF MINUTES EVAPORATED. THE DRIVER RETURNED TO TERMINAL TO BE RELOADED. PLYWOOD WILL BE USED IN THE FUTURE TO SEPARATE DRUMS AND TOTES TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE. THE LOAD WAS SECURED BUT THE DRUMS IN THE FRONT WERE NOT LOADED CLOSE ENOUGH TOGETHER TO PREVENT FOREWARD MOVEMENT IN A PANIC STOP.

DRUM HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE LOAD BEING RECEIVED, AND WAS BEING RELOADED ONTO TRAILER WHEN IT TIPPED OVER AND STRUCK THE LID RING. THE RING CAME LOOSE AND ALLOWED APPROX. 13 GALLONS OF WASTE TO SPILL. THIS TYPE OF DRUM TYPICALLY IS FRAGILE WHEN BUMPED OR DROPPED, AND THE LIDS DO NOT STAY ON. WHEN THE MATERIAL SPILLED, IT WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SWEPT UP.

THE DRUM WAS THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER (ASHLAND CHEMICAL, GREENVILLE, S.C.) PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS FOR HANDLING. DOCK ASSOCIATED WERE MET WITH PROPER HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WHEN USING A FORKLIFT WAS DISCUSSED.

THE POLICE ADVISED THAT THEY WERE SENDING THE GENTLEMEN TO OUR TERMINAL. WHEN HE ARRIVED HE WAS GIVEN A SHOWER AND A CHANGE OF CLOTHES AND WAS ADVISED TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED.  THE GENTLEMAN DID NOT GO TO HIS DOCTOR UNTIL FOLLOWING DAY TO BE CHECKED.  OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP FOR A HIRE CHECK AND DISCOVERED THE ODOR OF THE PRODUCT AND IN CHECKING HIS UNIT FOUND THAT THE AIR VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED.  HE CLOSED THE VALVE AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE UNIT FLUSHED WITH WATER TO REMOVE ANY RESIDUAL PRODUCT BEFORE PROCESSING TO HIS DESTINATION.

NOTIFIED RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER OF A PACKAGE OF RADIATION MATERIAL NOS THAT WAS OBSERVED TO BE WET AND BROKEN THROUGH AT THE PITTSBURGH INTERNAITONAL AIRPORT AT THE US AIR CARGO TERMINAL.  THE RSO CONTACTED LAURA DZURO OF AEROLINK INTERNATIONAL AND EXPLAINED THE NATURE OF THE PACKAGING FOR RADIOACITIVE MATERIAL IN LIQUID FORM AND THE MINIMAL EXTERNAL EXPOSURE HAZARD.  THE RSO GAVE PRECAUTIONARY INSTRUCTION TO HANDLE THE PACKAGE WITH DISPODSABLE GLOVES AND TO PLACE IT IN A PLASTIC BAY WITH THESE GLOVES UNTIL DMI PERSONNEL ARRIVED TO RECOVER THE PACKAGE.  THE DMI REPRESENTATIVE RECOVERED THE PACKAGE AT APPROXIMATELY 0945 ANE OPENED THE OVERPACKED CARTON USING DISPOSABLE GLOVES AFTER MONITORING THE PACKAGE FOR CONTAMINATION.  THE RSO NOTIFIED PERSONNEL AT THE PITTSBURGH, AIRPORT OF THE FINDING.  SINCE THE INCIDENT INVOLVED A SUSPECTED CONTAMINATED PACKAGE NOTIFICATION OF THE NRC WAS MADE IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49CFR 171.15 NECESSITATING THIS REPORT.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION OF DOT OHMT WAS ALSO MADE UNDER DOT E-8308 SECTON 9A.

column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS SOUTHBOUND ON NORTH CAROLINA HWY 52, AT A SPEED OF APPROX. 25-30 MPH HWY 52 IS A 4 LANE WITH HIGH GRASS MEDIUM AND CROSS TRAFFIC.  VEHICLE 2 PICKUP TRUCK WAS WAITING IN THE CROSSOVER LANE TO OUR LEFT.  AS WE APPROACHED, VEHICLE 2 PULLED ACROSS 2 FULL LANES BEFORE STRIKING THE LEFT FUEL TANK OF OUR TRACTOR.  THE FORWARD MOMENTUM OF OUR VEHICLE SWUNG V2 FORWARD AND THE REAR OF V2 WENT UNDER THE BELLY OF OUR CARGO TANK.  THE BED OF VEHCILE 2 STRUCK THE PROTECTIVE CAGE AND VALVES KNOCKING THEM OFF, SUBSEQUENTLY WE LOST THE ENTIRE LOAD OF CARBON DIOXIDE. THE HUMIDTY WAS VERY HIGH SO THE PRODUCT ALMOST INSTANTLY EVAPORATED. FEDERAL DOT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND OUR UNIT INSPECTED.  NO VIOLATIONS WERE NOTED.

column168: DOCK MAN FOUND CARTON LYING ON ITS SIDE AS HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE CARTON HAD FALLEN OVER IN TRANSIT DUE TO NOT BEING LOADED PROPERLY AT ORIGIN. SOME LIQUID PRODUCT ESCAPED BECAUSE OF LOOSE CAPS AND THE CARTON BEING ON ITS SIDE. CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. DOCK PERSONNEL MUST USE GOOD JUDGEMENT AND COMMON SENSE WHEN LOADING LIQUID HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON TRAILERS TO PREVENT TURNING OVER IN TRANSIT.

AT 1500 HOURS ON AUGUST 8TH IN EDGEMOOR YARD, A SWITCH CREW NOTICED AN ODOR FROM DOWX4786. A TEAM FROM STANDARD CHLORINE RESPONDED AND FOUND THE OUTLET VALVE OPERATING ROD HAD SLIPPED BELOW THE TOP PACKING. THE S.C. TEAM MADE A TEMPORARY REPAIR SO THAT THE CAR COULD MOVE THE SHORT DISTANCE INTO THEIR PLANT.

AT 1205 HOURS ON AUGUST 10TH IN NITRO YARD, P.B.& S. INSPECTOR DAN MCCOURT DISCOVERED GATX 58400 DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. A TEAM FROM P.B.& S. CHEMICAL RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE OUTLET CAP. THE CAR WAS THEN TAKEN INTO THE P.B.& S. PLANT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE RD, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 6-8 OUNCES OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM A BUNG CAP LOCATED ON THE LOWER SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BUNG CAP. TIGHTENING THE BUNG CAP DID NOT STOP THE LEAK AND THE DECISION WAS MADE TO PLACE THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRUM ITSELF WAS DEFECTIVE. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CONDUCT A TIRE AND LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED ON THE SIDEWALL OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIALS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER NOTED THAT THERE WAS A DENT ON THE DRUM AT THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WHICH WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE IN UNSHIPPABLE CONDITION.
DRUM WAS DAMAGED WHEN UNLOADING WITH DRUM TRUCK  DRUM WAS PUNCTURED

THIS PAIL ARRIVED IN NORFOLK DAMAGED. THERE WERE 52 PAILS TOTAL ON THIS SHIPMENT. THESE WERE TRIPLE STACKED ONTO A SKID, WITH NO DUNNAGE. ALSO, THIS WAS LOADED ON THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER, WHERE MORE MOVEMENT OCCURS. THE WEIGHT OF THE OTHER PAILS COMBINED WITH MOVEMENT OF THE FREIGHT, CAUSED THE PALLET TO FAIL, THUS CAUSING A PAIL TO BECOME PUNCTURED BY THE SKID. THIS SEEMS TO BE THE RESULT OF IMPROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES. THE ADDITION OF DUNNAGE PROBALLY COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS FORM OCCURING.

THE CARTON SHOULD HAVE BEEN PLACED ON A FOURWHEELED DOCK CART FOR TRANSFERRING FROM TRAILER TO TRAILER AS IT WOULD HAVE BEEN MORE STABLE THAN A SKID.

THROUGH-FREIGHT TRAILER WAS OPENED AT INTERMEDIATE TERMINAL FOR INSPECTION WHERE IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKAGE OF LIQUID ON CARDBOARD DUNNAGE FROM THREE CONTAINERS AND THE PAILS PROPERLY BLOCKED IN THE TRAILER. SHIPPERS SHOULD ENSURE THAT CAPS ARE TIGHT ON CONTAINERS AND DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD PROPERLY BLOCK IN CONTAINERS OF LIQUID HAZARDOUS FREIGHT.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE TWO LEAKING CONTAINERS AS HE WAS UNLOADING INBOUND TRAILER. THE PAILS HAD BEEN SHRINK WRAPPED ON A PALLET WHEN LOADED AT ORIGIN. THE DOCK PERSON DID NOT PROPERLY BLOCK THE FREIGHT IN AT ORIGIN AND DURING TRANSIT THE SHRINK WRAP BROKE WHICH ALLOWED SEVERAL PAILS TO FALL OVER. THE LOOSE BUNG CAPS ALLOWED SOME OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK OUT. FREIGHT TRANSFERRED TO OS&D WHERE THE BUNG CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND THEN THE FREIGHT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. DOCK PERSONNEL MUST PROPERLY BLOCK FREIGHT IN TO PREVENT IT FROM TURNING OVER IN TRANSIT. SHIPPERS SHOULD ENSURE THAT BUNG CAPS ARE TIGHT.

THE SKID WAS A SHORT SKID, AND THE FORKLIFT BLADES WERE TOO LONG.  THIS IS JUST A CASE OF THE DOCKWORKER NOT PAYING ATTENTION.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY WATCHING CAREFULLY AND NOT STICKING THE FORKLIFT BLADES TOO FAR UNDER THE SKID.

A RENEW OF PROPER HANDLING PROCEDURES WHEN UTILIZING A HAND TRUCK WAS CONDUCTED WITH ROUTE VAN DRIVER TO MINIMIZE THE POTENTIAL OF A SIMILAR RELEASE OCCURRY IN THE FUTURE.

AT FUEL STOP, APPROXIMATELY 3/4 MILE FROM DELIVERY LOCATION, DRIVER DISCOVERED ODOR FROM TRAILER WHILE DOING ROUTINE SAFETY INSPECTION OF HIS CARGO.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (16-20 OUNCES) WAS ON TRAILER FLOOR AROUND ONE OF CONTAINERS.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE SEEPAGE WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBANT PADS.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION (3/4 MI) IN AN ATTEMPT TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE TO OVERPACK THE DRUM.  DUE TO THE FACILLITY'S STRICT POLICY REGARDING OFF-SCHEDULE ARRIVALS, THE DRIVER WAS REFUSED ASSISTANCE.  DRIVER THEN RETURNED TO FUEL STOP WHERE HE DISCOVERED ADDITIONAL SEEPAGE FROM DRUM.  AGAIN THE DRIVER CONTAINED MATERIAL WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBANT PADS.  HAZ MAT ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP CONTACTED CORPORATE MATERIAL WITH SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBANT PADS.  HAZ MAT ENVIRONMENATAL GROUP CONTACTED CORPORATED ENSCO PERSONNEL WHO INSTRUCTED DRIVER TO IMMEDIATLEY RETURN TO DELIVERY LOCATION (CONSIGNEE) WHERE THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR CLEANED.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER APPEARED TO BE A NEW DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE DESIGNATED TSDF.  MO MATERIAL ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATEWAYS.

column42: TARS, LIQUID INCLUDING ROAD OILS AND CUTBACK BITUMENS
column168: #1 (CARGO TANK/TRUCK TRACTOR COMBINATION) WAS TRAVELING EAST ON I-80 IN THE RIGHT LANE.  #1 WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 20 MPH WITH THE EMERGENCY FLASHERS ON DUE TO CLUTCH PROBLEMS WITH TRACTOR.  #2 (REEFER/TRUCK TRACTOR COMBINATION) WAS ALSO TRAVELING EAST ON I-80 IN THE RIGHT LANE AT THE APPROXIMATE SPEED LIMIT.  #2 REAR ENDED #1 IN THE RIGHT LANE AND PUSHED #1 FURTHER DOWN THE ROAD.  WHEN #2 REAR ENDED #1 THE COLLISION CAUSED THE CARGO OF #1 TO RUPTURE AND SPILL THE CONTAINED PRODUCT.  THE RUPTURED CARGO TANK AND ITS CONTENTS IGNITED UPON IMPACT AND BURST INTO FLAMES. CARGO TANK OF #1 BECAME ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND WAS BURNT APPROXIMATELY 95%.  #2 WHICH REAR ENDED #1 ALSO WAS ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND WAS DESTROYED BY THE FIRE.  THE REEFER OF #2 SLIT OPEN AND SPILLED THE CONTENTS OF BEER ON THE ROADWAY.  DRIVERS OF BOTH #1 AND #2 WERE NOT INJURED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE TRAILER OF #1 AND BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER OF #2 WERE TOTALED.  THE BURNING MATERIAL AND THE BURNING EQUIPMENT WAS PUT OUT BY LOCAL FIRE AUTHORITIES.  THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS REMOVED AFTER THE STATE OF WYOMING ALLOWED TO DO SO.  THE ROADWAY BED DID SUSTAIN SOME DAMAGE.

AUGUST 11, 1994 APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT. APPROXIMATELY 100 GLALLONS OF THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRUCK. 17:00  DRIVER FOR CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PICKED UP TWO 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS OVERPACKED IN 85 GALLON METAL DRUMS.  THE DRUMS CONTAINED AN ISOCYANATE ADHESIVE WITH SOME METHYLENE CHLORIDE.  THE MATERIAL CARRIED THE HAZARDOUS WASTE CODE F002. 19:45  AS THE DRIVER WAS EXITING I-94 ONTO NAPIER ROAD, HE FELT THE TRUCK PULL TO THE LEFT.  HE PULLED INTO A TRUCK STOP, WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS AWAY.  WHEN HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK TO INSPECT, HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUT OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE TRUCK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. HE OPENED THE TRUCK AND IMMEDIATELY POURED ABSORBENT ON THE SPILL TO CONTAIN IT IN THE TRUCK. 19:55  AFTER CONTAINING THE SPILL, THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK.  HE DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL IN THE METAL DRUMS HAD REACTED AND PUSHED THE METAL DRUM THROUGH THE TOP OF THE OVERPACKS.  THE MATERIAL RELEASED WAS PRIMARILY CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRUCK.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT. 20:00  THE STATE POLICE, BENTON HARBOR POLICE, AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. 20:10  THE ACENCIES RESOPONDING TO THE SPILL AGREED THAT THE DRIVER HAD THE SPILL UNDER CONTROL. AUGUST 12, 1994 00:15  CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL ARRIVED TO HELP CLEAN UP THE AREA.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL HAD SOLIDIFIED.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE ASPHALT WAS SCRAPED UP AND PUT INTO DRUMS. 00:30  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE AMOUNT SPILLED DID NO CONSTITUTE AN RQ AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  NO FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. 04:30 A RESIDUE OF MATERIAL REMAINED ON THE ASPHALT, BUT ALL OTHER MATERIAL HAD BEEN CONTAINERIZED.  THE TRUCK WAS PARKED OVER THE RESIDUE, AS TO LIMIT ACCESS. 09:30  CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT CONTACTED LARRY POYNTER, MICHIGAN DNR TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.11:00  CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL RETURNED TO THE SITE TO REMOVE A 2' BY 4' AREA OF ASPHALT.  THE ASPHALT AND THE RESIDUE WERE PLACED IN DRUMS.  FIVE DRUMS (55 GALLON) OF CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE GENERATED AT THE SITE.  THE TWO ORIGINAL DRUMS AND THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE TRANSFERRED TO THE CONTROLLED WASTE FACILITY IN MENOMONEE FALLS, WISCONSIN.  THE TRUCK WAS PLACED AT A SECURE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IN CALUMET CITY, ILLINOIS. AUGUST 16, 1994 THE ASPHALT THAT HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE PARKING LOT WAS PATCHED. AUGUST 28-30 THE TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINATED BY SCRAPING THE MATERIAL FROM THE TRUCK AND REMOVING PARTS OF THE TRUCK WHERE THE MATERIAL COULD NOT BE REMOVED. THIS MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE GENERATOR OF THE MATERIAL IS CURRENTLY WORKING WITH THE MANUFACTURER TO DETERMINE HANDLING METHODS TO ENSURE THAT THE WASTE HAS COMPLETELY REACTED BEFORE IT IS OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING VEHICLE WHEN HE SMELLED FERMALDEHYDE ODOR.  HE IDENTIFIED PRODUCT LOADED ON A FLATBED CART.  PRODUCT WAS ON BASE OF CART AND LOOKED AS IF BOTTOM CORNER OF CARDBOARD HAD FAILED.  CONTAINER INSIDE CARDBOARD RUPTURED AT SEAM, AND WAS DRIPPING ONTO FLOOR & ABSORBED INTO CARDBOARD.  LEAKING ITEM HAD OTHER PRODUCT STACKED ON TOP OF IT ALTHOUGH NET OVERLY HEAVY).  ONCE DISCOVERED, TRAILER DOOR WAS CLOASED AND DECK AREA CLEANED THE LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.  PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED, ABSORBANT PLACED ON TRAILER BED AREA.  FUTURE CART LEADS WILL REDESIGNED TO PREVENT ANOTHER ACCURENCE.

column168: CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON GEORGIA HWY 113 APPROXIMATELY 1 3/4 MILES SOUTH I-20 WHEN IT LEFT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY ROLLING OVER 1 3/4 TIMES.  TRAILER HAD RUPTURED COMPARTMENTS (#1 & #4) RESULTING IN A 4196 GALLON SPILL OF GASOLINE.  OIL SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND CONDUCTED CLEANUP.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45 A.M. LOCAL PUD DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS DELIVERY'S IN HIS TRAILER.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOADED THE TWO DRUMS OF OLIN HUNT IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER 2273 WHICH WAS IN DOOR 47.  WHEN INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A PALLET THAT WAS LOADED IN FRONT OF THE PALLET OF OLIN HUNT HAD A NAIL STICKING OUT THE END.  WHEN THE PALLET WAS SET DOWN THE NAIL PROTRUDED THE BOTTOM RIGHT SIDE OF THE DRUM.  THE LOCAL PUD DRIVER WHO WAS INSIDE SECURING HIS LOAD CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER REPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL.  THEN DOCK SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED THE AREA AND THEN RESEARCHED ERG RESPONSE INFORMATION.  AFTER READING IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS A HEALTH HAZARD AND CAUSED VAPORS, DIZZINESS, AND VOMITING.  THEN VERNON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY AND CHEMICAL VAPORS WERE VERY SEVERE.  THEN WHN FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITHIN MINUTES THE WHOLE TERMINAL WAS EVACUATED EIGHTEEN EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO THREE LOCAL HOSPITALS FOR CHEMICAL INHALATION.  ALL EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY AND GIVEN TWO DAYS OFF.  SOME EMPLOYEES WERE RETURNED TO REGULAR WORK.  MOST OF THESE EMPLOYEES SHOULDN'T HAVE BEEN IN THE AREA BECAUSE OF EVACUATION WAS UNDER WAY.  THE REASON THIS HAPPENED HAD JUST COMPLETED THE DOT REQUIRED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAINING IN THIS LAST YEAR.  EMPLOYEES WERE INFORMED AGAIN WHEN IN THERE IS A EVACUATION AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL THEY ARE TO EVACUATE THE AREA AT ONCE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45, AUGUST 17, 1994, TRAIN INSE-6 TRAVELING WEST, WITH TWO LOCOMOTIVES AND 188 CARS, DERAILED NINE CARS (110 THROUGH118) AT MENTOR, OH.  AS A RESULT, THE 110TH CAR (ACRX72798), A LOAD OF VINYL ACETATE DERAILED AND TURNED ALMOST COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN.  DURING THE DERAILMENT, THE VAPOR INDUCTION VALVE WAS SMASHED AND BROKEN OFF.  AS A RESULT OF THE BROKEN VALVE, APPROXIMATELY 12,000 GALLONS OF VINYL ACETATE LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND.  AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, HULCHERS, WINTERS, O-H MATERIALS, AND A DUPONT RESPONSE TEAM WERE ALL SUMMONED TO ASSIST IN CONRAIL'S EMERGENCY EFFORT.

THE BUNG WAS FOUND TO BE TIGHT, SO THE LEAKAGE HAD TO BE DUE TO A DEFECTIVE GASKET.  LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED ON TOP OF DRUM.  DRUM WAS OFFLOADED AS TSDF, AND NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC., LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL, TO RINECO, LOCATED AT 1107 VULCAN ROAD IN BENTON, AR.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC., LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH, THE CONTAINERS FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO WERE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER VAN TRAILER.  DURING THIS OPERATION, THE FORKLIFT BEING USED TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CUBIC YARD BOXES CAUSING THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY REPACKAGED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND PLACED ALL CLEANUP DEBRIS IN THE NEW PACKAGE, WHICH CONTINUED TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR WILL BE REINSTRUCTED ON THE SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURES FOR THE USE OF FORKLIFTS WHEN LOADING OR UNLOADING VAN TRAILERS.

column168: TANKER WAS LOADED HALF FULL WITH 2200 GALLONS.  TANKER CONTAINS NO BAFFLES. AS DRIVER ACCELERATED TO PROCEED THROUGH INTERSECTION, LIQUID IN TANKER SURGED FORWARD AND BACK, FORCING PRESSURE ONTO REAR PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE CAUSING VALVE TO RUPTURE AND SPILL APPROXIMATELY 2-5 GALLONS OF LIQUID. HALF-FULL TANKERS ARE PRONE TO SURGES AND IF THERE ISN'T ENOUGH MATERIAL TO FILL A TANKER, WE MUST SEND HALF LOADS.  ALSO, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE IS A SAFETY DEVICE AND THE WEAKEST POINT OF A TANKER, RUPTURING WHEN PRESSURE REACHES 50 PSI. ATTACHED IS A COPY OF OUR INTERNAL SPILL REPORT AND A MAP INDICATING WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED.

ATSF'S CONTRACTOR FOUND SOURCE OF VAPOR TO BE LOOSE BOLTS (AND DETERIORATED RUBBER WASHERS) ON SAFETY RELEASE VALVE AND MANWAY. BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED ON THESE FIXTURES BY 1500. CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. NO LIQUID PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.

column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column168: YARD CREW NOTICED ODOR OF PROPANE AROUND CAR ACFX 18833. TRAIN MASTER ISOLATED AREA AND CONTACTED SHIPPER. SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THE PACKING NUT ON THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LOOSE. AGAIN FOR LEAKS. TESTS REVEALED NO FURTHER LEAKS. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0810 ON 8/31/94.

DURING ROUTINE INSPECTI0N, BOE INSPECTOR OERTLEY DISCOVERED A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK ON GATX 47381. RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND CAR WAS OK'D FOR MOVEMENT. A SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLED PRODUCT WAS EVIDENT AROUND THE TOP OF THE CAR.

DURING INBOUND INSPECTION, CAR INSPECTORS FOUND A SLOW LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF UTLX 41417 SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. SHIPPER SENT CONTRACTOR TO SECURE CAR. THE OUTLET CAP GASKET WAS REPLACED AND CAP TIGHTENED. AFTER FURTHER OBSERVATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE OUTLET VALVE WAS DEFECTIVE. THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR TRANSLOAD OF CONTENTS AND REPAIR OF VALVE.

PERSONNEL AT INERMODAL RAMP FACILITY DISCOVERED A SMALL PUDDLE OF LIQUID UNDER CONTAINER SECU 747135. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR ATTEMPTED TO SECURE AND TIGHTEN OUTLET VALVE FLANGE AND WAS UNABLE TO DO SO. VALVE WAS ENCAPSULATED AND CONTENTS OF CONTAINER WAS TRANSLOADED TO A SECOND CONTAINER. SPILLED LIQUID WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF.

A REPORT WAS RECEIVED FROM THE ROCK ISLAND, ILLINOIS POLICE DEPARTMENT INDICATING THAT A CLOUD OF VAPOR WAS EMITTING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON TANK CAR UTLX 80755, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, 2.2, UN1005. RAILROAD RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT ONE LIQUID VALVE AND THE VAPOR VALVE WERE NOT PROPERLY CLOSED AND NO VALVE PLUGS WERE IN PLACE. AFTER THE VALVES WERE PROPERLY CLOSED AND THE PLUGS INSERTED AND TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION. AFTER RECEIVING NOTIFICATION OF THE INCIDENT, THE SHIPPER CONDUCTED A CLASS TO INSTRUCT THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEES IN THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF TANK CARS AFTER UNLOADING.

column168: AT 07:30 A CALL ABOUT LIQUID DAMAGE ON BOXLINE 6 WAS MADE TO THE DMP AREA. J. PARRINO RESPONDED TO THE CALL WITH THE SPILL CART.  DECISION TREE RESPONSE WAS FOLLOWED.  AREA WAS RESTRICTED BY MARK OCHOTORENA AND FOLLOWED RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID.  (PH INDICATOR SHOWS CORROSIVE) NO FREE LIQUID, NO BOOTS NEEDED, NO ODOR-SCBA NOT USED.  THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CLEANED UP WITH SPEEDI-DRI ABSORBENT AND SOLUSORB. NO INJURIES OCCURED AS A RESULT OF THIS DAMAGE.  THE CONTAMINATED PACKAGES WERE CONTAINED IN SPILL TRAYS AND WAS BROUGHT TO DMP AREA AND PROCESSED THROUGH UPS DMP PROCEDURE. INFORMATION ABOUT THIS DAMAGE WAS FORWARDED TO SORT MANAGER FOR REVIEW.
NO REMARKS

TANK CAR GATX 25170 WAS DISCOVERED, IN THE CONWAY CLASSIFICATION YARD, WET AROUND THE SAFETY VENT.  AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR L.E. KERTING RESPONDED TO CONRAIL'S REQUEST FOR ASSISTANCE.  HE FOUND THE 100 LB.  DISC RUPTURED AND REPLACED SAME.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM PITNEY BOWES/MONARCH MARKETING LOCATED AT STATE ROAD 725 AND BYERS ROAD IN MIAMISBURG, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY AVE. IN CLEVELAND, OH.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK LOCATED ON THE SIDE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INDICATES THAT THE CONTAINER WAS PUNCTURED BY ANTOHER OBJECT CAUSING THE RELEASE.  FACILTIY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND THE MATERIAL CONTINUED ON TO THE INTENDED DESTINATION.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE LOCATION ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

THIS FAILURE CAUSED THE THREE RAILCARS TO ROLL UNRETARDED AND SUBSEQUENTLY STRUCK NATX78038, RESULTING IN DERAILMENT. DUE TO THE IMPACT OF THE DERAILMENT, THE B-END TRUCK BECAME OFF-CENTER AND ALLOWED THE B-END OF THE CAR TO IMPACT THE GROUND, RESULTING IN A PUNCTURE ABOUT 1-FOOT IN DIAMETER ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK, RESULTING IN A DISCHARGE OF APPROXIMATELY 23800 GALLONS OF LUBE OIL.  SUBSEQUENT EMERGENCY HANDLING PROCEDURES WERE IMPLEMENTED INCLUDING REMEDIAL GROUND CLEANUP AMD SOIL REMOVAL.

TIMING AND DESCRIPTION, ON WEDNESDAY AUGUST 10, 1994 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM, DON MACK AN ASHLAND DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 1700 BULK GALLONS OF ETHYL ACETATE AT FUJI CORPORATION IN WINNSBORO SC.  DURING THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, THE 3" X 2" COUPLING REDUCER BECAME DISCONNECTED DIRECTLY FROM THE 3" PUMP LINE, RELEASING AN ESTIMATED 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE POWER AND CONTAINED THE MATERIAL WITH CLEAN UP ABSORBENT. THE LINES WERE RECONNECTED AND THE DRIVER FINISHED PUMPING THE PRODUCT SAFELY INTO THE TANK.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED.  SOURCE OF INCIDENT, THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION COMMITTEE HAS DETERMINED SEVERAL FACTORS THAT JOINTLY CONTRIBUTED TO THE PRODUCT RELEASE:  1.  THE 3" X 2" COUPLING REDUCER IS SHAPED AT AN INWARD ANGLE AS TO SLOPE FROM THE 3" FITTING TO THE 2" CONNECTING LINE.  THE FITTING EARS AND RINGS ATTACHED TO THE COUPLING ALSO TURN INWARD TOWARD THE 2" SECTION OF THE REDUCER (SEE PHOTO).  THE VELCRO STRAP WAS USED TO SECURE THE FITTING HOWEVER, DURING THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, THE STRAP SHIMMIED LOOSE AND MOVED FORWARD TOWARDS THE 2" SECTION, THUS EXPOSING THE FITTING EARS TO OPEN.  1.  THE LAST PRODUCT PUMPED BEFORE THE ETHYL ACETATE WAS WHITE OIL. THIS WAS LATE TUESDAY AFTERNOON.  APPARENTLY, DURING THE REDUCER DISCONNECT, THE PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE FITTING ACTING AS A LUBRICANT TO SUPPORT THE VIBRATION OF THE TRUCK PUMP AND ULTIMATELY THE DISCONNECTED FITTING.  3.  THE PUMP CONNECTED WITH TRUCK #24233 WAS USED TO MAKE THIS PARTICULAR DELIVERY.  IT VIBRATES SIGNIFICANTLY AND IS A CONCERN IN INSURING THAT EXTRA PRECAUTION IS TAKEN TO SECURE ALL FITTINGS CONNECTED TO THE PUMP.  4.  THE VELCRO STRAP WAS IN PLACE HOWEVER, NO EFFORT WAS MADE TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL SECUREMENT, REALIZING THE CONE SHAPED FITTING HAD A TENDENCY TO SLIDE FORWARD.  TOM HALL DISCUSSED HIS PRACTICE OF TIEING THE VELCRO STRAP THROUGH THE RINGS IN PROVIDING ADDITIONAL STRENGTH, HOLDING THE FITTING EARS IN PLACE.  5.  DURING THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, DON MACK DECIDED TO INCREASE THE FLOW RATE BY TURNING UP THE PTO THROTTLE.  THIS ADDED ADDITIONAL PRESSURE TO THE 3" X 2" REDUCER THUS DISCONNECTING THE REDUCER FROM THE 3" PUMP PIPING CAUSING THE PRODUCT RELEASE.  HIS REASONING WAS TO PUMP THE PRODUCT FASTER.  TYPE OF INCIDENT, PRODUCT RELEASE OF 2 GALLONS OF ETHYL ACETATE CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THIS OCCURRED WHILE ATTEMPTING TO BULK UNLOAD 1500 GALLONS USING A 3" X 2" REDUCER FITTING.  UNSAFE ACTS, 1.  DRIVER DECIDED TO INCREASE PTO THROTTLE TO PUMP OFF MATERIAL AT A QUICKER RATE.  THE REDUCER COUPLER COULD NOT TAKE THE EXTRA PRESSURE.  2.  EVEN THOUGH THE VELCRO STRAPS WERE USED TO SECURE THE LINES, THE DRIVER DID NOT CONTINUE TO DOUBLE CHECK HIS CONNECTIONS THROUGHOUT THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE.   THE STRAP LOOSENED UP DURING 3" X 2" REDUCER.  IF THE STRAP WAS SECURE THE CORRECT WAY(INTER CONNECTED THROUGH THE RINGS) OR A LEAST CHECKED PERIODICALLY DURING THE MATERIAL TRANSFER, THE REDUCES WOULD NOT HAVE FAI

VW&R DRIVER, KARL PRICE, WAS ENROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO PPB TECH. IN SHELBY, NC WHEN A CAR STOPPED ABRUPTLY IN FRONT OF HIM.  KARL HAD TO APPLY HIS BRAKES VERY HARD TO PREVENT CONTACT WITH THE OTHER VEHICLE.  AT THIS TIME THE LOAD SECURING DEVICE FAILED AND PUNCTURED N 750# DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID OF WHICH 400# LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE SHOULDER OF HWY. 74 SERVICE ROAD.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND SODIUM BICARBONATE, PUT INTO RECOVERY DRUMS AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO VW&R, CHARLOTTE, NC FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE HANDLING OF THE MATERIAL NEUTRALIZATION, CLEANUP WAS WITNESSED BY THE CLEVELAND COUNTY EMERGENCY SERVICES.  DEWEY COOK (DEPUTY FIRE MARSHALL).

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: NELLA TANKER 9, A 1989 FREIGHTLINER, WAS ENROUTE FROM THE CHICO GASOLINE RACK TO GRASS VALLEY WITH 9100 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE.  THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN BY EUGENE G. GOODMAN, A 12 YEAR NELLA VETERAN WITH 28 YEARS F TANKER EXPERIENCE.  MR. GOODMAN WAS BORN 6/21/46.  HIS SSAN # IS 566-60-7067 AND CDL IS MC750468.  MR. GOODMAN WAS CLIMBING UP A HIL AT 7:30 PM ON HWY 20, APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES WEST OF GRASS VALLEY IN AN AREA KNOWN AS TIMBUCTU.  (THIS IS NOT A JOKE!)  MR GOODMAN ENCOUNTERED A 1 FOOT IN DIAMETER ROCK IN THE MIDDLE OF HIS LANE, AND SWERVED LEFT O PUT IT BETWEEN THE STEERING WHEELS.  IN SWERVING LEFT, THE TRAILER DEPARTED A STEEP SHOULDER ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE NARROW TWO LANE ROAD, IMPACTED A LARGE OUTCROPPING OF ROCK APPROXIMATELY THREE FEET OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT WHICH FLIPPED THE TRUCK ON ITS LEFT SIDE, CRUSHING THE ENTIRE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAB AND CARGO TANK AND FINALLY RESTING UPSIDE DOWN.  MR. GOODMAN WAS SECURED EFFECTIVELY BY HIS SEAT BELT AND WAS NOT INJURED.  THE TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS LEFT SIDE ALSO AND STRATED TO LEAK GASOLINE AT A RATE OF 1 GPM ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND INTO A NARROW DITCH ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE ROAD.  BY THIS TIME THE 4200 GALLON TRUCK WAS LEAKING FROM THE UPPER HATCH AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GPM.  IN TOTAL, 1100 GALLONS LEAKED FROM THE TRUCK TANK, AND 1324 FROM THE FRONT TRAILER TANK, A 1700 GALLON COMPARTMENT.  THE 3200 GALLON COMPARTMENT IN THE TRAILER DID NOT LEAK.  THE CARGO TANKS DID NOT FRACTURE AT ANY POINT.  THE ONLY LEAKS WERE FROM THE HATCH COVERES.  TOTAL FUEL LOSS WAS 2424 GALLONS AS DETERMINED BY MEASURING THE FUEL PUMPED AND HAULED FROM THE SITE.  BENETO TANK LINES WAS CALLED, AND THEY RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY WITH A TRUCK & TRAILER AND A HAZMAT TRUCK AND DRIVER.  BILL SHIRLEY AND DAVE BIRKMAN DROVE THE TANKER, AND TODD CRAIG DROVE THE BENETO HAZMAT TRUCK & TRAILER.  MR. CRAIG DESERVES SPECIAL MENTION FOR CUTTING TWO HOLES IN THE TANKS TO ALLOW EXTRACTION. SUTHERLAND OIL COMPANY RESPONDED WITH TWO TRUCKS.  THE SUPERVISOR WAS PIERRE.  ALL CREWS REPSONDED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON AUGUST 12, 1994 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:10 AM, JAMES M. KRISFALUSI WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON US HWY 6 AND DESCEND LOVELAND PASS.  AS MR. KRISFALUSI APPROACHED MILE POST 218, FOR SOME UNKNOWN REASON MR. KRISFALUSI LOST CONTROL OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER HE WAS OPERATING, AND OVERTURNED ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF THE ROAD.  THE VEHICLE ROLLED AT LEAST ONCE ON THE ROADWAY AND SHOULDER, THEN ROLLED A DISTANCE UP THE BANK, AS THE VEHICLE ROLLED BOTH ON THE SHOULDER AND UP THE BANK, HOLES WERE PUNCHED IN THE SIDES OF THE CARGO TANK AND THE SLIDING MOTION RIPPED THE SIDES OPEN AT THE BULKHEADS OF THE CARGO TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 5500 GALLONS OF FUEL, AVIATION TURBINE ENGINE, 3 UN1863 LEAKED FROM HOLES IN THE TANK SIDES.  J.C. TRUCKING, INC. WAS NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 8:15 AM.  AT THAT TIME WE IMMEDIATELY CALLED WEST HAZMAT TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM OFFICER COLLEY OF THE COLORADO STATE PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SECTION WANTING TO KNOW THE STATUS OF THE RESPONSE PERSONNEL.  OFFICER COLLEY INFORMED ME AT THAT TIME THAT HE BELIEVED MOST OF THE LOAD HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE CARGO TANK.  OFFICER COLLEY ALSO INFORMED ME THAT U.S. HWY 6 WAS CLOSED AND WOULD BE FOR SOME TIME, AT THAT TIME I CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO MAKE A REPORT TO THEM, I TALKED TO MARK LEWACK WHO ASSIGNED REPORT 254961 TO THE INCIDENT.  MR. LEWACK ALSO INFORMED ME THT HE WOULD NOT NOTIFY E.P.A. AND THERE WAS NO NEED FOR ME TO DO THAT.  WEST HAZMAT, UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE CALLED FOR MACHINERY TO BEGIN EXCAVATING CONTAMINATED SOIL, SET UP BOOMS AND PADS TO ABSORB FREE PRODUCT AND BUILD A SIPHON POND TO GATHER PRODUCT FROM DITCH ALONG ROADWAY.  WE TRANSFERED ABOUT 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE WRECKED TANK TO ANOTHER TRUCK FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO DENVER.  APPROXIMATELY 1000 YARDS OF SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND REPLACED WITH CLEAN ROAD BASE.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JERRY PEERY SUPERVISOR, CLAIMS SERVICES, PALESTINE, TEXAS, THAT A TRAILER HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO A CUSTOMER IN OAKLAND CA, AND UPON OPENING THE TRAILER AT THE DOCK, DISCOVERED THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED DURING TRANSIT. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED KIM KIRBY, SHIPPING/RECEIVING, PACIFIC AMERICAN WAREHOUSE, OAKLAND, CA, AND DEVELOPED TRAILER KLFU122743 WAREHOUSE, WAS REPORTED LEAKING TO HER BY THE DRAYMAN WHO ORIGINALLY WENT TO THE UP OAKLAND RAMP TO PICK UP THE TRAILER FOR PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  REAMP PERSONNEL NOTED NOTHING UNUSUAL ABOUT THE CONDITION OF THE TRAILER FOR PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  RAMP PERSONNEL NOTED NOTHING UNUSUAL ABOUT THE CONDITION OF THE TRAILER, AND RELEASED IT TO THE DRAYMAN.  THE DARYMAN DELIVERED THE TRAILER TO PACIFIC AMERICAN, WHERE IT WAS SIGNED FOR, AND SPOTTED.  THE DRIVER COMMENTED ON SMELLING AN UNUSUAL ODOR, HOWEVER, THERE WERE NO PHYSICAL SIGNS OF PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS OPENED THE FOLLOWING MORINING, AT WHICH TIME THE CONTENTS WERE OBSERVED TO HAVE LEAKED.  PACIFIC AMERICAN CONTACTED HUB CITY, THIRD PARTY SHIPPER, REQUESTING REMEDIATION ASSISTANCE.  HUB CITY MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL TO RE-COOP THE LADING.  UPRR ALSO REQUESTED AN INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER BY KEVIN CORTIS, CONTRACTED INSPECTOR FOR THE RAILROAD.  UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER, ONE OPENED HEAD DRUM LOCATED IN THE CENTER OF THE LOAD, WAS NOTED WITH THE LID ASKEW.  THE CLAMP SHIFTED SLIGHTLY DURING TRANSIT, THE LID CAME LOOSE, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND THE LOOSE PRODUCT CLEANED AND PREPARED FOR DISPOSAL.  DUE TO THE LIMITED AMOUNT AND TYPE OF COMMODITY SPILLED, THERE WERE NO NOTIFICATIONS MAD TO ANY OF THE REGULATORY AGENCIES.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF HILL, CORRIDOR MANAGER, HARRIMAN DISPTACH CENTER, OMAHA, THAT BOB SCHUT, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA, REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING ITS CONTENTS FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED SUPERVISOR SCHUT, WHO STATED THE CARMEN WERE INSPECTING THE INBOUND TRAIN WHEN THEY OBSERVED LIUQID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR AT A RATE OF OF SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN YARD TRACK 205 AND THE AREA SECURED PENDING INSPECTION.  THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE XPCYR-06 AT 1530 HOURS, THURSDAY, AUGUST 11, 1994.  MANAGER COOPER, IN COMPANY WITH MANAGER STUDENT DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE BOTTOM WASHOUT.  THE 8 BOLT BLIND FLANGE PLATE HAD ONE OF THE SECUREMENT BOTLS MISSING, HOWEVER, THIS DID NOT APPEAR TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  THE PLATE AND BOLTS WERE DAMP WITH PRODUCT AND IT CULD NOT BE DETERMINED EXACTLY WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM AS ALL OF THE BOLTS WERE TIGHT.  THE BEST GUESS IS THE INTERNAL CLOSURE WAS LEAKING AND BY PASSING THE EXTERNAL INSPECTIIN PLATE AT THE SURFACE CONTACT AREA TO THE WASHOUT.  UPON OPENING THE MANWAY COVER PLATE, DEVELOPED THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN BOTH ENDS OF THE CAR, AND WHEN THE COLAR IN THE WASHOUT THAT ACTS AS A GUIDE FOR THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WAS ASKEW, AND IT IS UNKNOWN IF THIS HAD ANY EFFECT FROM REFILLING THE WASHOUT, SEVERAL BUCKETS OF SAND WAS DUMPED FROM REFILLING THE WASHOUT, SEVERAL BUCKETS OF SAND WERE DUMPED INTO THE WASHOUT AND SURROUNDING AREA TO FORM A BARRICADE.  ONCE THE CENTER AREA OF THE CAR WAS COVERED WITH THE SAND, THE LEAK STOPPED.  UPON CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, IT WAS LEARNED THE CAR WAS BEING LOADED FOR SHIPMENT WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE SAME AREA.  THE CAR WAS EMPTIED AND SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO STOP THE LEAK, WHICH COULD NOT BE ACCOMPLISHED.  THE CAR WAS BAD ORDERED AND LINED TO THE REPAIR SHOP.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NO FURTHER NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

GEORGE GREVE LOADED ON 08-02-94 AT HAZARDOUS WASTE RECOVERY, INC.  (HWR) IN KANSAS CITY, O.  THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST DOCUMENT NO. 12618 INDICATED THE WASTE TO BE RQ, WASTE FLAMMABLE SOLID, N.O.S. (PAINT SOLIDS/DEBRIS), CLASS 4.1, UN1325, PGIII, WITH WASTE CODES OF D001, F003, AND F005.  THIS LOAD OF WASTE WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS, INC. MORGAN CITY, LA. MR GREVE STOPPED ENROUTE AT THAYOR, MO. TO REST AT HOME.  HE OBTAINED PERMISSION FROM Y & D COMPLETE AUTO REPAIR-RON YORK TO PARK THERE FOR A FEW HOURS.  UPON RETURNING TO HIS TRUCK, MR. GREVE FOUND HIS TRAILER BURNED WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT ON THE SCENE.  ME. GREVE REQUESTED THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT USE AS LITTLE WATER AS POSSIBLE AND THAT THEY EITHER DIG A DITCH OR BUILD BURMS TO CATCH THE RUN OFF.  ON OR ABOUT 3:00PM, A HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE ARRIVED AND TOOK OVER OPERATIONS IN CONJUNCTION WITH MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES.  TRAID TRANSPORT, INC. DISPATCHED A TRUCK AND ROLL OFF TRAILER WITH THREE (3) BOXES PER HAROLD MCNALLY OF H.W.R.  THIS TRUCK WITH DRIVER WAS ON THE SCENE UNTIL 08-05-94, ALSO MR. GREVE REMAIN ON THE SCENE.  WE ALSO HAD ANOTHER TRUCK ROLLOFF TRAILER WITH DRIVER ON THE SCENE.  ALL BURNED MATERIAL WAS REMOVED PLUS SOME SOIL AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL, THEN DELIVERED TO MARINE SHALE RPROCESSORS, INC. IN MORGAN CITY, LA.  AS THE TIME OF THIS REPORT BEING REPORTED, NO DETERMINED OF ACUTAL CAUSE OF IGNITION HAD BEEN STATED.  CHEMICAL IMCOMPATIBILITY WAS THE MOST PROBABLE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.  IF CHEMICAL INCOMPATIBILITY IS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF IGNITION, H.W.R. SHOULD IMPLEMENT PROGRAMS TO BE USED TO TRAIN OR REFRESH EMPLOYEES ABOUT CHEMICAL COMPATIBILITY BEFORE LOADING.

column168: THE SPECIAL AGENT'S OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AT 1000 HRS 81694 OF THE ABOVE RAILCAR FIRE. AT 1005 THE SAN ANTONIO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND THE UP SOSAN RAIL YARD WAS EVACUATED. BY 1030 HRS THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD PLACED A VOLUNTARY EVACUATION ON 80 HOMES AFFECTING 150 PEOPLE. IN CONSULTATION WITH THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT AND THE INCIDENT COMMANDER FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THE DECISION WAS MADE TO OPEN THE RAILCAR DOORS. THIS WAS TO ALLOW THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR TO COOL BELOW IGNITION TEMPERATURE OF THE PRODUCT CAUSING THE FIRE TO EXTINGUISHED AND ALL BUT A SMALL AMOUNT OF FUMES CEASED EXITING THE CAR. THE SURROUND EVACUATION WAS LIFTED, WHILE THE SOSAN YARD OPERATION REMAINED ABATED. LATER INTO THE INCIDENT A COMPRESSED GAS (CO2) WAS INJECTED INTO THE HOT SPOT OF THE CARGO THROUGH THE HOLE IN THE CAR FLOOR THAT THE MOLTEN PRODUCT HAD CAUSED. AFTER THE MOLTEN PRODUCT FLOW WAS CONTAINED WATER WAS INJECTED ON TO THE HOT SPOT IN THE SAME MANNER COMPLETELY EXTINGUISHING THE FIRE. THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE UNLOADED AND PLACED IN ROLL-OFF TRANSPORT CONTAINERS FOR LATER RECLAMATION AND TRANSPORTATION. THE SURROUNDING AREA AFFECTED BY THE EXTINGUISHING EFFORTS WAS CLEANED WITH THE GUIDANCE OF THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION. ALL REMEDIATION WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF UNDER THE SAME SCRUTINY. THE RAILCAR WAS BAD ORDERED FOR FULL MECHANICAL INSPECTION. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE FIRE ORIGINATED AT OR NEAR A DOOR THAT HAD BEEN REPAIRED BY WELDING THIRTY MINUTES PRIOR TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE FIRE.

MANAGER MECHANICAL MTCE. J. ROSS NOTIFIED MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATIOIN SAFETY S. D. WHITED THAT CAR RCRX 1216 HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR WHEN MOVED.  FURTHER THAT CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED AND TRACK BLOCKED. THE OTHER TWO BOLTS HAD BEEN LOOSENED TO WHERE THE HOUSING WAS LEANING AWAY FROM THE CAR.  WHITED REPLACED BOLT AND TIGHTENED THE OTHER TWO BOTLS SECURING LEAK.  WHITED COINTACTED MR. CHARLES BURNETT OF REGENT CHEMICAL & RESEARCH, PORT AUTHOR, TEXAS TELEPHONE 1-800-231-1807 AND WHO ADVISED THAT HIS COMPANY HAD MADE INSPECTION OF THE CAR BEFORE LOADING AT RUBICON CHEMICAL GEISMAR, LA., TELEPHONE 504-672-6141.  WHITED CONTACTED MR. J. ROSS MANAGER MECHANICAL MTCE., UNION RAILROAD DUPO, IL. AND WHO ADVISED THAT NO MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE HAD BEEN ON OR AROUND CAR OTHER THAN WHEN CAR WAS SET TO THE REPAIR TRACK AND TRACK LOCKED UP.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, TOM SMITH ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  HE TIGHTENED THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. column168: AS REPORTED AUGUST 11 BY ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES OF NEVADA, INC. (ET), ON BEHALF OF MST TRUCKING COMPANY OF 2385 S. 300 WEST, SUITE 202, SALT LAKE CITY, UTAH 84115, ET RESPONDED TO CLEANUP OF A SPILL OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AS A RESULT OF A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT INVOLVING A TRACTOR TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL FROM THE TRACTOR AND THREE (3)- 5 GALLONS CONTAINERS OF PAINT RELATED MATERIALS SPILLED ONTO SOIL AT THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  NO REPORTABLE QUANTITIES OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE RELEASED IN THE ACCIDENT EXCEPT FOR THE OIL PRODUCT.  A PROTECTIVE NOTIFICATION WAS FILED WITH THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #256140) FOR THE INCIDENT ACCORDING TO 49 CFR 171.15, BECAUSE NORTHBOUND INTERSTATE 15 WAS CLOSED OFF FOR APPROXIMATELY 90 MINUTES WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS POSITIONED FOR TOWING.  THE ACCIDENT AT MILE MARKER 55 NORTH BOUND ON INTERSTATE 15 NEAR THE APEX, NEVADA CUT-OFF IN CLARK COUNTY, NEVADA AT ABOUT 6:30 AM ON AUGUST 4.  THE SPILL OCCURRED WITHIN SECTION 17, TOWNSHIP 19 SOUTH, RANGE 63 EAST.  ET ALSO OVERPACKED THREE (3)- 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINERS OF NITRIC ACID WHICH HAD SMALL BUNG LEAKS AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  THE ACID WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER SECTION OF THE VEHICLE.  THERE ARE NO KNOWN OR ANTICIPATED ACUTE OR CHRONIC HEALTH RISKS ASSOCIATED WITH THE RELEASE.  NO PERSONS WERE INJURED, NOR WERE THERE ANY UNIQUE OR UNUSUAL CIRCUMSTANCES AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO THREATS TO ANY WATERWAYS.  ALL SPILLED MATERIALS FROM THE INCIDENT HAVE BEEN PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED. SEVEN (7) WASTE DRUMS FROM THE PAINT RELATED MATERIALS WERE SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL USING MANIFEST NUMBER 94313.  THE PETROLEUM CONTAMINATED SOILS (16.51 TONS) FROM THE OIL PRODUCT SPILL WERE PROFILED, DELIVERED AND ACCEPTED INTO THE APEX INDUSTRIAL WASTE LANDFILL ON MANIFEST NUMBER 94316.

FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, JON MOOTS ENTERED THE BELLY. TECHNICIAN MOOTS PH'D THE LEAKING MATERIAL. THE PH PAPER TURNED A BLUE COLOR WHICH INDICATED THIS WAS A POSSIBLE CAUSTIC MATERIAL. THIS WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH CONTAINED 3, 2 QUART CAPACITY PLASTIC RECEPTICLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES. THE LABEL ON THE PLASTIC RECEPTICLES STATED THIS MATERIAL WAS "PROFESSIONAL STRENGTH LIQUID PLUMMER". THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WAS HELD AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER. THIS WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT PENDING INVESTIGATION AND RELEASE BY THE FAA.

(A - C) ON AUGUST 16 AND 17, 1994, THREE ROADRUNNER TRUCKING UNITS: 9568-4529 COMP.648676 ED NEWCOMB* 9470-4567 COMP.648677 PAUL CAMPBELL* 9777-5017 COMP.648678 JOE ANDREWS*  WERE LOADING AT TECH-IRON, ADELANTO, CA, WITH 22 PALLETS OF SUPERSACKS ON EACH TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS TENDERED AS "FERROUS SULFATE" UN3077, A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, NOT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. FOUR BLOCKS FROM THE SHIPPER, THE ADELANTO, CA POLICE STOPPED ALL THREE UNITS, AT DIFFERENT TIMES, BUT IN THE SAME GENERAL AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED, AND THE DRIVERS WERE TOLD THE SUPER-SACKS WERE LEAKING AND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS "SULFURIC ACID" WHICH IS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, AND HAS AT LEAST FIVE DIFFERENT UN OR NA NUMBERS.  ALL THREE UNITS WERE ESCORTED BACK TO THE SHIPPER, AND THE TRAILERS WERE DROPPED AND IMPOUNDED BY THE POLICE DEPARTMENT FOR ENVIRONMENTAL VIOLATIONS CAUSED BY TECH-IRON.  THE MORNING OF AUGUST 17, 1994, BEGINNING AROUND 7:00 A.M., ATTEMPTS WERE MADE BY PAM MUSGRAVES TO CONTACT AT LT. GUNDERSON OF THE ADELANTO, CA POLICE DEPARTMENT WHO WAS IN CHARGE OF THE CONFISCATION OF THE LOADS.  AT 8:20 A.M. (AUGUST 17, 1994) LEN WAS ABLE TO CONTACT A TOM DALLING OF TECH-IRON WHO SAID HE KNEW NOTHING ABOUT THE THREE LOADS. WHILE I WAS TALKING TO HIM, THE LOCAK POLICE ARRIVED AT THE FACTORY AND MR. DALLING SAID HE WOULD CALL ME BACK.  A FEW MINUTES LATER LT. GUNDERSON CALLED, AND HE TOLD ME WHAT HAPPENED, AND WHY:  "TECH-IRON HAS BEEN UNDER SURVEILLANCE FOR ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEMS.  THEY HAVE NO LICENSE OR PERMITS TO OPERATE THE KIND OF FACILITY THEY ARE RUNNING.  TECH-IRON HAS SET ROADRUNNER UP AND YOU (ROADRUNNER) HAVE BECOME AN INNOCENT VICTIM OF THESE VIOLATIONS" I ASKY YOU? GUNDERSON STATED THAT THE PRODUCT IS "SULFURIC ACID" AND NOT "FERROUS SULPHATE".  I ASKED WHY THE THREE UNITS WERE STOPPED AND GUNDERSON STATED THAT SOME OF THE SACKS ON EACH TRAILER WERE LEAKING.  ALSO, IT WAS THOUGHT THAT ROADRUNNER WAS IN ON THE VIOLATIONS, BUT IT WAS LEARNED AT ONCE THAT THIS WAS NOT TRUE.  THE PRODUCT WAS DAMAGING OUR TRAILERS AND THE TRAILER TARPS, AND TIE DOWN EQUIPMENT MUST ALL BE DECONTAMINATED.  THE EPA WAS SCHEDULE TO ARRIVE AT TECH-IRON ON AUGUST 17, 1994 FOR AN INSPECTION.  I ASKED LT. GUNDERSON IF THERE WERE ANY CHARGES PENDING AGAINST ROADRUNNER AND HE STATE, "NO WAY".  HE FURTHER STATED TECH-IRON WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR ALL DECONTAMINATION OF OUR EQUIPMENT. AT THAT POINT, HE SAID HE HAD TO GO AND THE CONVERSATION WAS OVER BUT COULD BE RESUMED LATER IF NEEDED.  LT. GUNDERSON'S TELEPHONE NUMBER IS (619)254-6572.  LATER THIS MORNING, I VISITED WITH ALL THREE DRIVERS. EACH DRIVER WILL BE SENDING ME A STATEMENT AS TO WHAT HAPPENED WITH EACH OF THEM FROM THEIR ARRIVAL AT TECH-IRON TO THE TIME THEY DROPPED THEIR TRAILERS BACK AT TECH-IRON.  ON AUGUST 17, 1994 AT 5:15 P.M., MIKE KHOUDARY CALLED LEN AT HOME AND SAID CATHY PERRY WAS ON THE TELEPHONE STATING THAT THE THREE (3) TRAILERS AT ADELANTO, CA WERE SETTING IN THE STREET.  IT WAS MY UNDERSTANDING FROM OUR DRIVERS THAT
NO REMARKS

column168: ON 082094 CR FORMAN DAVE HOAGLAN CALLED CTS SPECIALIST M. KELLY AND STATED THAT WHILE CONDUCTING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE MUSKOGEE YARD, A TRAIN CREW HAD KNOCKED A TOTE BIN CONTAINER OFF OF A FLAT CAR ONTO THE GROUND CAUSING THE BIN TO SPLIT ON ONE SIDE AND THE TOP CLOSURE TO OPEN UP. HOAGLAN STATED THAT ONE LARGE QUANITY OF THE MATERIAL HAD SPILT ONTO THE GROUND AND THAT IT HAD BEEN FORCASTED TO START RAINING THAT NIGHT.  UPON RECEIVING THIS INFORMATION KELLY CONTACTED FRED DYCE WITH MIDWEST CARBIDE AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SPILLAGE.  MR DYCE ADVISED THAT THE PRODUCT NEEDED TO BE REMOVED FROM THE GROUND AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO PREVENT IT FROM BECOMING WET AND FORMING ACETYLENE GAS.  UPON RECEIVING THIS INFORMATION KELLY CONTACTED SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES AND INFORMED THEN OF THE SPILL AND THE URGENCY OF THE CLEAN UP.  KELLY ALSO ADVISED SOONER THAT THE SHIPPER MIDWEST CARBIDE WOULD BE ON THE SCENE AND ASSIST THEM WITH TRANSPORTING THE PRODUCT BACK TO THEIR PLANT IN PRYOR, OK.  THE SPILL HAD BEEN CLEANED UP BY 2030 HRS AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE SHIPPERS PLANT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.

column168: SENIOR HAZMAT AGENT ZERWECK WAS CALLED TO A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE MESQUITE TOFC/COFC RAMP.  TRAILER CSXZ 238216 WAS LEAKING FROM THE WOODEN FLOOR OVER THE RIGHT REAR TANDEM TIRES.  ZERWECK OPENED THE DOOR REMOVING SEAM CHEMREX 00265 AND FOUND THE LEAK WAS FROM THE SECOND ROW OF DRUMS FROM THE DOOR ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  MARK HORTON WITH CHEMREX WAS ADVISED AND HIRED EMTECH TO REMEDIATE.  EMTECH ARRIVED AT 1830 AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEANED THE TRAILER WITH ALL MATERIAL PLACED IN THE DRUM.  THE DRUM HAD APPARENTLY BEEN CRIMPED WHEN LOADED CAUSING THE LEAK.  EMTECH WAS FINISHED AT 1930 AND THE TRAILER WAS REBLOCKED BY RAMP PERSONNEL.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY , WAS NOTIFIED BY DICK SULLIVAN, CORRIDOR MANAGER, HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER, OMAHA, WHO STARTED JOE MOSHIER, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING LIQUID FROM ONE OD THE SIDE COMPARTMENTS. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED SUPERVISOR MOSHIER, WHO STARTED THE CARMEN WERE WORKING AN INBOUND ATSF INTERCHANGE CUT IN YARD TRACK C-4 WHEN THEY OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE SIDE COMPARTMENTS.  THE LIQUID WAS MAKING CONTACT WITH THE NORTH SIDE RAIL AND ICING UP A THREE FOOT SECTION OF THE TRACK.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN THE YARD TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A 1/4 INCH LIQUID SAMPLE LINE.  THE LIQUID SAMPLE LINE EXITS THE LOWER PORTION OF THE TANK CAR AND TEE'S; ONE SIDE TO THE LIQUID (BARTON) GAUGE, THE OTHER TO A TRYCOCK HAD SOME UNKNOWN DAMAGE WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO SPRAY OUT FROM BETWEEN THE LINE AND TIGHTENING NUT.  ATTEMPTS TO SECURE THE FITTING MET WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS.  AS THERE WAS NO IN LINE SHUT OFF VALVE, THE LIUQID SPRAY WAS DIVERTED DOWN ONTO THE GROUND BELOW THE COMPARTMENT, TO PREVENT ANY DAMAGE TO THE TRUCK.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE PRAXAIR FACILITY AT MANUEL REQUESTING ASSISTANCE.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE ONTARIO PLANT RETURNED THE TELEPHONE CALL AND AFTER DESCRIBING THE RELEASE, STATED THEY WOULD DRIVE TO YERMO TO REPAIR THE CAR SOMETIME AROUND 0400 HOURS.  AT 12OO HOURS, TUESDAY, AUGUST 30, 1994, MANAGER COOPER WAS CONTACTED BY GARY HUNTER, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, STATING THE TANK CAR WAS STILL LEAKING, AND HE WAS UNAWARE OF ANY PRAXIAR PERSONNEL EVER ARRIVING TO REPAIR THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER AGAIN CONTACTED THE PRAXIAR PLANT AT MANUEL, AND DEVELOPED THEIR CUSTOMER SERVICE GROUP HAD REQUESTED THEY SEND A TECHNICAN, AS THE ONTARIO PLANT ONLY SERVICED CARS CONTAINING HYDROGEN.  UPON LOCATING THE REPRESENTATIVE THAT WAS TO DO THE REPAIRS, A DETAILED EXPLANTAION WAS PRESENTED ON THE CONDITION OF THE CAR AND A REQUEST TO CALL AND CONFIRM THE NEEDED REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED.  ON WEDNESDAY MORNING, AUGUST 31ST, MANAGER COOPER AGAIN CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER SERVICE GROUP FOR PRAXAIR, REQUESTING AN UPDATE ON THE REPAIRS, AS THE SERVICE TECHNICIAN HAD NOT CALLED WITH ANY INFORMATION. MANAGER COOPER WAS INFORMED THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN CURTAILED AT 1900 HOURS TUESDAY NIGHT.  AS THERE WAS NO WAY TO REPAIR THE LEAK, THE LIQUID SAMPLE LINE WAS CRIMPED TO CURTAIL THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND TYPE OF RELEASE, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR CORROSIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY DICK SULLIVAN, COORIDOR MANGER, HARRIMAN DISPTACH CENTER, OMAHA, WHO STATED DOUG MAUGHAN, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTED A TANK CAR LEAKING ITS CONTENTS FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MANAGER MAUGHAN, WHO STATED THE TANK CAR WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS BY THE EAST END SWITCHER, WHEN THE CREW NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE EAST END OF THE RIP TRACK (#521) AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  ALL EIGHT OF THE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THE COVER PLATE GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  THE COVER PLATE WAS CLOSED AND THE SECUREMENT BOTLS PROPERLY TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE THE CLOSURE HAD NO FURTHER LEAKAGE, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WHICH REMAINED ON THE SURFACE OF THE CAR, NO FURTHER ACTION OR NOTIFICATIONS WERE REQUIRED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AT 1240 HOURS AUGUST 28,1994 MTO STEVE HAMPTON CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE ADVISING THAT TRAIN CREW ON SCHOZ-26 WAS IN PROCESS OF SETTING OUT CAR HS 903170 ACCOUNT MATERIAL WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM CONTAINER NSAU 401888.  CAR BEING PLACED ON HOUSE TRACK AT BAVERIA, KANSAS MP 194.8 FURTHER CONTAINER WAS MARKED "KEEP AWAY FROM FOOD STUFFS".  ON GROUND INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CONTAINER WAS ON "B" END AND THERE WAS A "AMBER" COLORED SUBSTANCE ON DECK UNDER CONTAINER AND TO REAR.  IT APPEARED THAT THE MATERIAL HAD STOPPED LEAKING AND MATERIAL WAS STARTING TO SET UP HAVING THE CONSTANCY OF "LARD", THE PH WAS 4.  REMOVED INTACT SEAL "EXPEDITORS INTL 2133" FROM RIGHT REAR DOOR AND FOUND THAT ONE 55 GALLON DRUM HAD FALLON TOWARD THE RIGHT SIDE OF CONTAINER AND PUNCTURED ANOTHER 55 GALLON DRUM THAT WAS SETTING AT RIGHT SIDE WALL.  THE HOLE WAS BETWEEN THE TWO DRUM CHIMES WHICH ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL.  IT APPEARED THAT THE WOODED PALLET HAD COLLAPSED AND ALLOWED DRUM TO FALL INTO A VOID THAT WAS IN THE LOAD.  SOME OF THE DRUMS APPEARED TO BE LOADED INDIVIDUALLY AND OTHERS WERE ON PALLETS WITH SHRINK WRAP APPLIED.  SOME PALLETS HAD THREE DRUMS AND OTHERS HAD FOUR DURMS.  NOTED NO BLOCKING OR BRACING AND THE DRUMS WERE NOT SEPERATED OR NESTED IN THE CENTER.  AFTER INSPECTION APPLIED SEAL "UP X 140922"  MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR CAR TO BE TAKEN TO SALINA, KANSAS SO THAT THE PUNCTURED DRUM COULD BE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND CONTAINER CLEANED.  THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER SHOWN ON SHIPPING PAPERS 509-927-1045 WOULD NOT ANSWER.  AUGUST 29,1994 AT 1000 HOURS MADE CONTACT WITH "CONNIE" 800-233-7824 AND WAS ADVISED THAT SOMEONE WOULD CONTACT THIS OFFICE WITH WHAT ACTION WOULD BE REQUIRED.  AFTER SEVERAL CONVERSATIONS AT 1205 HOURS MR. KEITH FERGUSON OCEAN MANGER WITH EXPEDITORS INTERNATIONAL 206-872-3860 CALLED AND ADVISED THE SHIPPER OF THE MATERIAL WAS "BULLHIDE LINER" HOWEVER HIS COMPANY HAD LOADED THE CONTAINER.  SEVERAL OPTIONS WERE DISCUSSED AND IT WAS DECIDED THAT HAZMAT RESPONSE INC WOULD BE CONTRACTED TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT. PERSONNEL FROM HAZ/MAT AT WICHITA, KANSAS WOULD OVERPACK THE ONE DRUM AND PARTIALLY CLEAN THE FLAT CAR THEN THE LOAD WOULD BE BROUGHT TO KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI TO BE OFF LOADED AND TRANSFERED INTO ANOTHER CONTIANER AS THIS MATERIAL HAD TO BE IN HOUSTON, TEXAS FOR EXPORT NO LATER THAN SEPTEMBER 9,1994.  CONTACTED MR. RONALD GROSSMAN OF THE BULLHIDE LINER AND OBTAINED AN "MSDS" FOR THE MATERIAL "BULLHIDE 2000 PART A".  MR. GROSSMAN'S RECOMMENDATION WAS THAT ANYONE ENTERING THE CONTAINER USE CHEMICAL SPLASH SUITE, FULL FACE RESPIRATOR WITH SPECIAL ACID-ORGANIC FILTERS, RUBBER GLOVES AND BOOTS UNTIL THE ONE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND EXCESS ON CONTAINER FLOOR HAD DRIED INTO A SOLID MATERIAL.  HE ALSO FURNISHED A LIST OF ALL THE MATERIAL IN THE LOAD.  UNDER THE PRESENT REGULATIONS THE REPORTING REQUIREMENT IS 1 LB SO MR. GROSSMAN ADVISED THE NRC AND AND USEPA REGION 7.  MR. STINE CONTACTED KANSAS DEPART

ON AUGUST 16, 1994, AT APPROXIMATELY 13:00, YARDMASTER CURTIS PROTHRO CONTACTED S/A DEAN WOMACK AND INFORMED HIM THAT TANK CAR, GATX 14580, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING AT THE END OF REISOR YARD.  AT APPROXIMATELY 13:30, S/A WOMACK ARRIVED AT REISOR YARD AND FOUND TANK CAR GATX 14580 SETTING AT THE EAST END OF TRACK 12.  S/A WOMACK INSPECTED THIS CAR FINDING NO DEFECTIVE GASKETS OR FITTINGS.  THERE WAS FRESH PRODUCT ON TOP OF THIS CAR, AND IT APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  S/A WOMACK EXAMINED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, WHICH WAS SET AT 35 POUNDS.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE DEFECT.  S/A WOMACK CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER, BOB STINE, INFORMING HIM OF THIS INCIDENT.  MR. STINE AND S/A WOMACK DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY VALVE OPENED WHEN THE CAR WAS MISHANDLED DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.CAR WAS RELEASED AT 16:00.  S/A WOMACK CONTACTED THE STATE POLICE (#94-3423*ANN*),  DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND CHEMTREC.  S/A WOMACK SPOKE WITH WALTER STARNES OF MERICHEM AND WILLIAM WARREN OF OLIN; BOTH WERE INFORMED OF THE DETAILS OF THIS INCIDENT.

AT 16:30 ON AUGUST 18, 1994, WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION, CTS MGR LERCH NOTED LOADED CAR CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WITH DRIED PRODUCT AROUND BASE OF SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY AND SIDES OF CAR.  INSPECTION OF STANDARD MIDLAND 2-INCH SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY WITH SPLASH BAFFLE, LOCATED OUTSIDE LOADING PLATFORM "A" END, REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  MGR LERCH REPLACED FRANGIBLE DISC; MAKE/TYPE NOT LEGIBLE DUE TO POOR CONDITION WITH A NEW BS&B #100 DISC WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  CAUSE OF RELEASE DUE TO HYDRAULIC SURGE OF PRODUCT WITHIN CAR. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: RECEIVED A CALL FROM OFFICER ELLIOTT OF THE HIGHWAY PATROL ADVISING THAT ONE OF OUR TANKERS HAD ROLLED ON HWY 62 N/BOUND OF PALM SPRINGS.  ADVISED TO GET A HAZMAT TEAM; A TOW TRUCK OR TWO AND IMMEDIATELY COME TO THE SCENE.  CALLED CAL WEST ENVIRONMENTAL; CALLED RIVERSIDE TOWING ADVISED ALL TO MEET AT DESERT HOT SPRINGS.  ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS; CHP OFFICER ELLIOTT ADVISED THIS WAS A RIVERSIDE COUNTY INCIDENT SINCE IT WAS IN THE DESERT HOT SPRINGS AREA; I, MARY WINSOR, IMMEDIATELY WENT TO THE HOSPITAL AND RETURNED ALONG WITH OUR AGENT; THE DRIVER HAD GONE TO THE HOSPITAL AND RETURNED WITH A CUT ON HIS HAND; SHAKEN UP FROM THE INCIDENT.  HE GAVE THIS ACCOUNT.  HE WAS DRIVING ON HWY 62 WHEN HE HEARD A POPPING SOUND AND THE TRAILER BEGAN TO SWIRVE; WHILE LOOKING IN HIS MIRROR TO SEE IF A TIRE BLEW; HE FELT THE TRAILER GO OVER A BURM; HE PULLED THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROAD, HOWEVER THE ROAD RAN OUT CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLL AT LEAST ONCE, POSSIBLY TWICE. THE RIVERSIDE HAZMAT TEAM WAS THERE UNDER THE DIRECTION OF MR. ASBURY. MR. ASBURY HAD CALLED FOR A HELICOPER TO BRING IN A SPECIAL FITTING THAT WOULD CUT INTO THE TANK, ALLOWING A STINGER TO PUMP OFF THE 7535 GALLONS OF JP5 THAT WAS ON THE TRUCK; A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAS COME THRU THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM; A SMALL POOL WAS UNDER THE VAPOR RECOVERY OVERFLOW SYSTEM.  THE HAZMAT TEAM AND FIRE DEPARTMENT OF LOS ANGELES WERE IN THEIR SUITS AND THE HOLE WAS CUT IN THE TANKER; MR. RABICO, PRESIDENT OF OWNER OPERATORS PETROLEUM ADVISED MR. MOLINE THAT THE SPECIAL UNIT SHOULD BE PLACED OVER THE VAPOR AREA BECAUSE OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM, HOWEVER MR. MOLINE ADVISED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO CUT THE HOLE IN THE FRONT OF THE TANKER. AS THEY DID, THE PRESSURE FROM THE TANK BEING ON ITS SIDE FOR OVER FIVE HOURS BECAUSE OF THE PRECAUTIONS TAKEN, THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM OPENED UP CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF JP5 TO GO INTO A SANDY DESERT AREA.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT STOPPED THE PUMPING AND RELEASED THE PRESSURE, PUMPING THE PRODUCT INTO ONE OF OUR TANKERS THAT EMPTY RETURNING FROM TWENTY-NINE PALMS.  THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF IN ABOUT 4 HOURS; AT THAT TIME THE TWO TOW TRUCKS THAT HAD BEEN WAITING ALL DAY, BEGAN TO PULL THE TANKER AND THE TRACTOR OUT OF THE VALLEY THAT IT HAD ROLLED INTO.  AS THEY DID, THERE WAS MORE PRODUCT IN THE VAPOR SYSTEM WHICH BEGAN TO COME OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKER CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO GO INTO THE HIGHWAY; CAL WEST ENVIRONMENTAL BEGAN TO STOP THE PRODUCT LEAK, AND CAL TRANS THAT WAS THERE, ALSO, BEGAN TO HELP STOP THE LEAK.  IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 11:00 P.M. AND THE RIVERSIDE HAZMAT  TEAM WHICH HAD LEFT AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 P.M. CAME BACK BECAUSE OF THE SPILL; BOTH THE DIESEL TANK AND THE TANKER BEGAN TO LEAK.  OWNER OPERATORS STAFF BEGAN TO PUMP OFF THE PRODUCT PUTTING IT INTO THE TWO TRUCKS.  THE HAZ MAT TEAM ORDERED ANOTHER PUMP TRUCK TO COME AND PUMP OFF THE REST OF THE PRODUCT, WHICH WE DID; ALL TANKS WERE EMPTIED, TH

column168: ON 8/26/94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0309 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF AIRBORNE EXPRESS INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS. THE SHIPMENT HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION ATTACHED OR ACCOMPANYING IT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD  BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON IT. THERE WAS NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND TWENTY-TWO OUNCE GLASS BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES. THERE WERE NO MEANS TO POSITIVELY SECURE THESE CLOSURES. TWO OF THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE BROKEN, EACH BOTTLE CONTAINED FRAGRANCE SAMPLES. THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY AREA PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column168: TRAILER ARRIVED IN ROCKY MOUNT, NC.  UPON OPENING REAR DOOR, ODOR WAS RECOGNIZED.  MADE CALL THE CHEMTREC.  JIM LONG, AT CHEMTREC, SAID TO ISOLATE THE CARTON.  WE PULLED TRAILER FROM DWELL INTO YARD.  MR LONG NOTIFIED BILL MARMS WITH FISHER SCIENTIFIC.  MR MARMS CALLED ME AND REQUESTED WE CALLED LOCAL WASTE HANDLER TO DISPOSE.  HE SAID THE ODOR WOULD DISSIPATE.  CALLED OUT SAFETY DEPARTMENT, GARY HOWELL.  GARY NOTIFIED AETC, ADVANCE ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGY CORPORATION, TO RESPOND. AETC SENT Z REPORTS TO SITE.  THE USED SPECIAL CLOTHING TO ATTEND TO DOING ITEM.  THEY RETIGHTENED THE CYLINDER VALVES, RECOOPED THE CYLINDERS, AND ALSO TRIPPLED BAGGED THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER.  THIS IS THE REASON I AM UNABLE TO PROVIDE SOME OF THE PACKAGING INFORMATION REQUESTED ABOVE.  AETC FIELD REPRESENTATIVE STATED ON THEIR REPORT IMPROPER PACKING AS THE REASON FOR THE INCIDENT.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: EMPLOYEE KIM KROLL, WHILE PERFORMING HER ASSIGNMENT AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER, WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP A LEAKING PACKAGE CONTAINING AMMONIA SOLUTION NH40H. APPROXIMATELY .5 GALLON HAD LEAKED OUT DUE TO A LOOSE CAP. THE RESPONSE SHEET CALL FOR ALL PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, INCLUDING THE SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS. WHILE USING THE "SCBA" KIM FAILED TO OBTAIN AN AIR-TIGHT SEAL ON HER MASK RESULTING IN INHALATION AND EYE EXPOSURE TO THE SUBSTANCE VAPORS. KIM EXPERIENCED A TIGHT CHEST, HEADACHE AND BURNING EYES SENSATION. KIM WAS TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR TREATMENT AND OBSERVATION AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED THE SAME NIGHT. KIM MISSED THE NEXT DAY OF WORK AND RETURNED TO WORK FULL DUTY.
